{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782930817610,"sessionID":"ses_0e10e5929ffe88XcmihhZxWbsA","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"call_ed67e7d35bcc49b5ac7ea0ca","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"grep -rn \"goal-prompt.md\" \".opencode/specs/deep-loops/031-deep-loop-issues-with-gpt-opencode\" 2>/dev/null"},"output":"...output truncated...\n\nFull output saved to: /Users/michelkerkmeester/.local/share/opencode/tool-output/tool_f1ef54247002rkP84AnPJsMaKJ\n\n.opencode/specs/deep-loops/031-deep-loop-issues-with-gpt-opencode/007-gpt-behavioral-hardening-research/research/lineages/glm-max/prompts/_lineage-synthesis.cjs:376:- \\`research-prompt.md\\` (KQ1-KQ9, boundaries, stop conditions); \\`../goal-prompt.md\\` (symptoms)\n.opencode/specs/deep-loops/031-deep-loop-issues-with-gpt-opencode/007-gpt-behavioral-hardening-research/research/lineages/glm-max/prompts/_lineage-synthesis.cjs:394:- \\`../goal-prompt.md\\` — packet objective + observed symptoms\n.opencode/specs/deep-loops/031-deep-loop-issues-with-gpt-opencode/007-gpt-behavioral-hardening-research/research/lineages/glm-max/prompts/_lineage-driver-1.cjs:31:  sources: ['../001-deep-agent-router-and-orchestration/research/research.md', 'deep.md', 'orchestrate.md', 'ai-council.md', '005-gpt-verification-smoke/verification-smoke.md', '006-host-hard-identity-fix5/decision-record.md', 'mode-registry.json', 'goal-prompt.md'],\n.opencode/specs/deep-loops/031-deep-loop-issues-with-gpt-opencode/007-gpt-behavioral-hardening-research/research/lineages/glm-max/prompts/_lineage-driver-1.cjs:123:    { claim: 'Symptom \"overthinks / needs literal deterministic instructions\" -> the judgment-dependent Deep Route field (orchestrate.md:207) plus free-text Priority table that omits 2 of 4 deep modes forces GPT into inference it handles poorly.', evidence: 'orchestrate.md:95-105,207; goal-prompt.md OBSERVED SYMPTOMS' },\n.opencode/specs/deep-loops/031-deep-loop-issues-with-gpt-opencode/007-gpt-behavioral-hardening-research/research/lineages/glm-max/prompts/_lineage-driver-1.cjs:127:  sources: ['orchestrate.md:95-105,162,207', '../001-deep-agent-router-and-orchestration/research/research.md §1,§3.1', 'research-prompt.md:21', 'goal-prompt.md OBSERVED SYMPTOMS'],\n.opencode/specs/deep-loops/031-deep-loop-issues-with-gpt-opencode/007-gpt-behavioral-hardening-research/research/lineages/glm-max/prompts/_lineage-driver-1.cjs:142:    { claim: 'Evidence the agent-layer fix (002-004) does NOT address mode D: those phases only hardened routing/identity; no phase hardened the advisory-vs-mandatory distinction in command prose.', evidence: 'research-prompt.md:14-19 (002-004 scope); goal-prompt.md WHAT 031 ALREADY ESTABLISHED' },\n.opencode/specs/deep-loops/031-deep-loop-issues-with-gpt-opencode/007-gpt-behavioral-hardening-research/research/lineages/glm-max/prompts/_lineage-driver-1.cjs:160:    { claim: 'The two symptoms have different operator descriptions: \"stuck\" implies a halt/wait state; \"slow\" implies completion with long duration. They are observably separable in the report.', evidence: 'research-prompt.md:21; goal-prompt.md OBSERVED SYMPTOMS' },\n.opencode/specs/deep-loops/031-deep-loop-issues-with-gpt-opencode/007-gpt-behavioral-hardening-research/research/lineages/glm-max/prompts/_lineage-driver-1.cjs:165:  sources: ['research-prompt.md:21', 'goal-prompt.md OBSERVED SYMPTOMS', '../001-deep-agent-router-and-orchestration/research/research.md §3.1,§9'],\n.opencode/specs/deep-loops/031-deep-loop-issues-with-gpt-opencode/007-gpt-behavioral-hardening-research/research/lineages/glm-max/iterations/iteration-008.md:9:- **The two symptoms have different operator descriptions: \"stuck\" implies a halt/wait state; \"slow\" implies completion with long duration. They are observably separable in the report.** [SOURCE: research-prompt.md:21; goal-prompt.md OBSERVED SYMPTOMS]\n.opencode/specs/deep-loops/031-deep-loop-issues-with-gpt-opencode/007-gpt-behavioral-hardening-research/research/lineages/glm-max/iterations/iteration-008.md:16:- goal-prompt.md OBSERVED SYMPTOMS\n.opencode/specs/deep-loops/031-deep-loop-issues-with-gpt-opencode/007-gpt-behavioral-hardening-research/research/lineages/glm-max/iterations/iteration-007.md:10:- **Evidence the agent-layer fix (002-004) does NOT address mode D: those phases only hardened routing/identity; no phase hardened the advisory-vs-mandatory distinction in command prose.** [SOURCE: research-prompt.md:14-19 (002-004 scope); goal-prompt.md WHAT 031 ALREADY ESTABLISHED]\n.opencode/specs/deep-loops/031-deep-loop-issues-with-gpt-opencode/007-gpt-behavioral-hardening-research/research/lineages/glm-max/iterations/iteration-006.md:11:- **Symptom \"overthinks / needs literal deterministic instructions\" -> the judgment-dependent Deep Route field (orchestrate.md:207) plus free-text Priority table that omits 2 of 4 deep modes forces GPT into inference it handles poorly.** [SOURCE: orchestrate.md:95-105,207; goal-prompt.md OBSERVED SYMPTOMS]\n.opencode/specs/deep-loops/031-deep-loop-issues-with-gpt-opencode/007-gpt-behavioral-hardening-research/research/lineages/glm-max/iterations/iteration-006.md:19:- goal-prompt.md OBSERVED SYMPTOMS\n.opencode/specs/deep-loops/031-deep-loop-issues-with-gpt-opencode/007-gpt-behavioral-hardening-research/research/lineages/glm-max/iterations/iteration-001.md:24:- goal-prompt.md\n.opencode/specs/deep-loops/031-deep-loop-issues-with-gpt-opencode/007-gpt-behavioral-hardening-research/research/lineages/glm-max/resource-map.md:10:- `../goal-prompt.md` — packet objective + observed symptoms\n.opencode/specs/deep-loops/031-deep-loop-issues-with-gpt-opencode/007-gpt-behavioral-hardening-research/research/lineages/gpt-critical/logs/fanout-lineage.out:35:{\"type\":\"tool_use\",\"timestamp\":1782897205745,\"sessionID\":\"ses_0e30e0717ffe0AOyqAZM72PE2n\",\"part\":{\"type\":\"tool\",\"tool\":\"read\",\"callID\":\"call_JQNXyMAeg2Wfnc1oAfscn3Q0\",\"state\":{\"status\":\"completed\",\"input\":{\"filePath\":\"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/deep-loops/031-deep-loop-issues-with-gpt-opencode/007-gpt-behavioral-hardening-research/research/research.md\",\"offset\":1,\"limit\":2000},\"output\":\"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/deep-loops/031-deep-loop-issues-with-gpt-opencode/007-gpt-behavioral-hardening-research/research/research.md</path>\\n<type>file</type>\\n<content>\\n1: # Research: GPT Behavioral Hardening Follow-Up (Packet 031, Phase 007) — Consolidated Synthesis\\n2: \\n3: > Consolidates two independent 30-iteration fan-out lineages run against the same charter (`../research-prompt.md`): **glm-max** (`zai-coding-plan/glm-5.2`, reasoning `max`) and **gpt-fast-high** (`openai/gpt-5.5-fast`, reasoning `high`). Both ran `stopPolicy: max-iterations` — early convergence signals were treated as telemetry only, not a stop condition. Both completed 30/30 iterations and answered all 9 KQs with file:line evidence. Full lineage detail: `lineages/glm-max/research.md`, `lineages/gpt-fast-high/research.md`.\\n4: \\n5: ---\\n6: \\n7: ## 0. Cross-Lineage Agreement (high confidence)\\n8: \\n9: Both models, working independently with different reasoning styles, converged on the same core verdicts:\\n10: \\n11: - **Do not unpark FIX-5/host-identity now.** Phase 005 never reached a real leaf dispatch (blocked upstream by `cli-opencode` self-invocation guards) — its \\\"inconclusive\\\" result is neither proof the agent-layer fix works nor proof it doesn't. Both lineages treat the operator's real-world symptom report as sufficient to keep the question open, but not sufficient on its own to trigger FIX-5.\\n12: - **Keep `ai-council` as `mode: all`.** Converting to subagent-only breaks a documented, working depth-0 parallel-seat path that the reported symptoms don't actually implicate. Both lineages instead recommend a cheaper, reversible fix: align/add route-proof header naming for council (a concrete naming drift exists between `mode-registry.json`'s `mode: council` and `deep_ai-council_auto.yaml`'s `mode: ai-council` / `target_agent: deep-ai-council`).\\n13: - **Harden `@orchestrate` by delegating to `deep.md`**, not by expanding orchestrate's own judgment-heavy prose. `deep.md` is deterministic (table lookup + one bounded clarification gate); `orchestrate.md`'s `Deep Route:` field currently requires GPT to self-derive `mode=`/`execution=` from a Priority table that doesn't even list `deep-context`/`deep-review`. The smallest fix: orchestrate detects a `/deep:*` or deep-leaf request, dispatches `@deep` with the Deep Route header resolved from `mode-registry.json`, and stops — no self-derivation.\\n14: - **A sub-agent-enforcement plugin is feasible**, home: `system-skill-advisor` (it already owns routing metadata + a drift-guard). Scope: a pre-dispatch hook that asserts route-proof fields resolve against `mode-registry.json`, fails-closed or warns on mismatch. **Hard limit, confirmed by both lineages: this is a detection layer, not hard identity** — a schema-valid, route-matched artifact that does semantically wrong-mode work still passes the plugin (the same false-negative class phase 002's route-proof validator was built to catch). It does not substitute for the KQ1 external smoke or for FIX-5.\\n15: - **A GPT-vs-Claude benchmark is needed and cheap to build**: 4 deep modes × 2 model families, measuring route-proof correctness (4-field match) and latency, run repeatably as a baseline now and a regression gate after the orchestrate/plugin fixes land.\\n16: - **Propagation scope** (both lineages name the same files): `.opencode/agents/orchestrate.md` (+ `.claude` mirror), the 4 deep command prompt/YAML seams, `.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-ai-council/scripts/orchestrate-topic.cjs` (route-proof naming), and the new plugin surface under `system-skill-advisor`. Codex parity stays blocked on the pre-existing TOML-location doc contradiction (out of scope here).\\n17: \\n18: ---\\n19: \\n20: ## 1. Where the Lineages Diverge (needs a human/planning decision)\\n21: \\n22: ### 1.1 A fourth mis-route mechanism (glm-max finding, not in gpt-fast-high)\\n23: \\n24: glm-max's KQ2 answer splits the operator's four symptoms into **four** mechanisms, not the three (routing/latency/artifact) gpt-fast-high uses:\\n25: \\n26: | Symptom | Mechanism | Class |\\n27: |---|---|---|\\n28: | Wrong sub-agent invoked | orchestrate lacks deep-context/deep-review rows + soft identity | mis-routing (existing A/B/C taxonomy) |\\n29: | **Stuck on pre-defined flows** | **GPT reads soft advisory command-prose as a hard gate** | **NEW — \\\"Mode D\\\"** |\\n30: | Overthinks / needs literal instructions | judgment-dependent Deep Route field forces inference | mis-routing + Mode D |\\n31: | Slow as `@orchestrate` | role-resolution overhead (`subagent_type:general` + no CLI agent flag) | latency — distinct from routing |\\n32: \\n33: Mode D matters because it is **not fixed by hard identity**: FIX-5 (host hard identity / process isolation) prevents wrong-agent dispatch, but does nothing about GPT halting on an advisory step it misreads as mandatory. If Mode D is real and significant, the orchestrate/deep.md hardening (KQ4) and the literal-instruction-following pattern (KQ7) are the actual fix for a chunk of the reported symptoms — not FIX-5, and not even the enforcement plugin. gpt-fast-high's `stuck_latency` failure class is adjacent but conflates \\\"halts on a misread gate\\\" with generic slowness; it doesn't isolate the misread-as-gate mechanism the same way.\\n34: \\n35: **Recommendation:** treat Mode D as a confirmed-worth-tracking hypothesis (glm-max marks it CONFIRMED-in-mechanism, INFERRED-in-magnitude — no GPT-vs-Claude telemetry exists yet to size it). The KQ6 benchmark should explicitly measure it: does GPT halt/loop on advisory-only prose sections in a way Claude does not, independent of route-proof correctness? Fold this into whichever phase builds the benchmark.\\n36: \\n37: ### 1.2 Phase-ordering disagreement (smoke-first vs. fix-first)\\n38: \\n39: - **gpt-fast-high's order:** 008 external smoke+benchmark → 009 orchestrate unification → 010 council alignment → 011 optional plugin → 012 FIX-5 checkpoint. Philosophy: measure before changing anything.\\n40: - **glm-max's order:** 008 prompt-layer hardening (orchestrate delegation + council header + propagation) → 009 enforcement plugin → 010 external smoke + benchmark → 011 regression gate → 012 conditional FIX-5. Philosophy: land the cheap, low-blast-radius, reversible fixes first, then measure with the fixes already in place so the benchmark tests the *improved* system, not just the baseline.\\n41: \\n42: Both are internally coherent; neither lineage was told to reconcile against the other (each ran as an isolated fresh-context lineage per the fan-out design). **This is the one decision this research does not resolve and the next planning step must pick.** Note in favor of glm-max's order: the benchmark becomes more informative if it measures the system after the reversible, low-risk fixes (orchestrate delegation, council header) are already in place — a pre-fix baseline number is nice-to-have but not required to decide whether to proceed with those fixes, since both lineages already agree the fixes are worth doing regardless of benchmark results. Note in favor of gpt-fast-high's order: measuring first establishes a clean \\\"before\\\" number for anyone who later questions whether the fixes actually helped.\\n43: \\n44: ### 1.3 A sharp meta-risk both plans share (glm-max, stated more explicitly)\\n45: \\n46: Every \\\"unpark FIX-5\\\" decision criterion in both lineages — and in the packet's own existing decision-record.md — depends on running the external, non-OpenCode-shell smoke that phase 005 was never able to run. glm-max states the risk plainly: **\\\"if no OPENCODE_PID-free shell exists, the gate cannot fire and FIX-5 stays parked indefinitely — the same trap as 005/006.\\\"** This is not a new problem this research solves; it is the single precondition every downstream recommendation in this document depends on. Before committing to any phase-008-through-012 plan, confirm a genuine external shell (or fresh isolated worktree with no `opencode` ancestor process) is actually available and will be used — otherwise the entire \\\"decisive smoke\\\" plan is unreachable in practice, exactly as it was in phase 005.\\n47: \\n48: ---\\n49: \\n50: ## 2. Consolidated KQ Answers\\n51: \\n52: | KQ | Consolidated Answer | Agreement |\\n53: |---|---|---|\\n54: | **KQ1** — Decisive smoke evidence | Design an 8-run (4 modes × 2 models) external, non-OpenCode-shell smoke with explicit PASS criteria: no `OPENCODE_*` env, no `opencode` ancestor process, route-proof fields (`mode`/`target_agent`/`agent_definition_loaded==true`/echoed `resolved_route`) all match. Native/Claude baseline run identically for comparison. | Full agreement |\\n55: | **KQ2** — Real-world mis-route mechanism | A mix of mechanisms, not one class: mis-routing (missing orchestrate rows), a **new Mode D** (advisory-prose read as hard gate — glm-max), and latency (role-resolution overhead) as a **separate, non-routing** issue. | Partial — glm-max's Mode D is additive, not contradicted |\\n56: | **KQ3** — ai-council subagent-only | Do not convert. Keep `mode: all`; fix the council route-proof naming drift instead. | Full agreement |\\n57: | **KQ4** — orchestrate hardening v2 | Delegate deep-dispatch to `deep.md`/`mode-registry.json`; replace judgment-filled Deep Route derivation with a deterministic \\\"resolve via deep.md and STOP\\\" rule. Orchestrate keeps decomposition/evaluation/synthesis authority — only mode-resolution moves. | Full agreement |\\n58: | **KQ5** — enforcement plugin | Feasible, home `system-skill-advisor`, pre-dispatch hook asserting route-proof resolvability. Detection only — explicitly not hard identity; does not close the schema-valid-but-wrong-mode gap. | Full agreement |\\n59: | **KQ6** — GPT-vs-Claude benchmark | 4 modes × 2 models, route-proof correctness + latency, run as baseline now and regression gate later. Should also measure Mode D specifically (§1.1). | Full agreement + one addition |\\n60: | **KQ7** — literal-instruction-following pattern | Generalize `deep.md`'s pattern (deterministic table + one bounded clarification gate + pre-resolved dispatch header + fail-closed consistency check) to routing surfaces only. Do not apply to leaf/execution agents — that would remove the evidence-responsive flexibility Claude currently has and the packet must preserve. | Full agreement |\\n61: | **KQ8** — propagation scope | `orchestrate.md` (+ `.claude` mirror), 4 deep command seams, `orchestrate-topic.cjs` (council route-proof naming), new plugin surface. Codex parity stays out of scope (pre-existing TOML blocker). | Full agreement |\\n62: | **KQ9** — FIX-5 unpark decision | Wait. Do not unpark now; do not close as permanently sufficient either. Unpark **only if**, after the cheaper layers (orchestrate delegation, plugin, council header) land and the external smoke runs, the benchmark shows GPT route-proof `< 4/4` on any mode while Claude achieves `4/4` — a negative gate proving insufficiency, sharper than 006's original (never-exercised) positive trigger. | Full agreement on substance; glm-max's negative-gate framing is more decisive and is the recommended wording |\\n63: \\n64: ---\\n65: \\n66: ## 3. Recommended Next-Phase Breakdown\\n67: \\n68: Reconciling both proposals, in the order this synthesis recommends (fix-first, per §1.2's reasoning), continuing numbering from phase 007:\\n69: \\n70: 1. **008 — Prompt-layer hardening.** Orchestrate→deep.md delegation (KQ4); route-proof header propagation across the 4 command seams (KQ7/KQ8); ai-council route-proof naming alignment (KQ3). Bundle `.claude` mirrors in the same phase. Low blast radius, fully reversible — do not gate this on the smoke harness below.\\n71: 2. **009 — Detection-layer plugin.** KQ5 enforcement plugin in `system-skill-advisor`.\\n72: 3. **010 — External smoke + benchmark baseline.** KQ1's 8-run harness and KQ6's benchmark, run *after* 008+009 land, from a confirmed genuine external (non-OpenCode) shell — **verify that shell exists before starting this phase** (§1.3). Explicitly measure Mode D (§1.1) alongside route-proof correctness and latency.\\n73: 4. **011 — Regression gate + KQ9 decision.** Apply the negative-gate criterion from KQ9 against the 010 results.\\n74: 5. **012 (conditional) — FIX-5 / host hard identity.** Unpark only if 011's gate fires.\\n75: \\n76: ---\\n77: \\n78: ## 4. Residual Risks Carried Forward\\n79: \\n80: - **Gate runnability (highest-priority residual):** the entire 010-through-012 chain is unreachable without a confirmed `OPENCODE_PID`-free external shell. Confirm this before committing to the plan above.\\n81: - **Mode D magnitude is inferred, not measured** — the 010 benchmark must size it or this remains a hypothesis.\\n82: - **Plugin semantic-blindness is a known, accepted limit** — the smoke/benchmark, not the plugin, is what actually validates leaf-dispatch correctness.\\n83: - **Mis-route taxonomy (modes A/B/C) and the FIX-1…FIX-5 ranking remain operator-asserted axioms**, carried from the predecessor research (`../001-deep-agent-router-and-orchestration/research/research.md` §0) and not re-validated by this research pass. The KQ1 smoke is the stated path to validating them, not this document.\\n84: - **Codex parity** stays deferred (pre-existing TOML-location contradiction, out of scope for this packet).\\n85: \\n86: ---\\n87: \\n88: ## 5. Convergence Report (both lineages)\\n89: \\n90: | Lineage | Model | Iterations | Stop reason | Questions answered | Notes |\\n91: |---|---|---|---|---|---|\\n92: | glm-max | `zai-coding-plan/glm-5.2`, reasoning `max` | 30/30 | `maxIterationsReached` | 9/9 | 0 salvaged/failed iterations; adversarial re-checks at iters 8, 11, 13, 19, 22, 25, 26 |\\n93: | gpt-fast-high | `openai/gpt-5.5-fast`, reasoning `high` | 30/30 | `max_iterations` | 9/9 | 30/30 iterations required stdout-salvage recovery for the canonical JSONL append (a runtime robustness note, not a research-quality issue — narrative content and citations are intact) |\\n94: \\n95: Both lineages' `newInfoRatio` trends declined well below typical early-stop thresholds by iteration ~10-12 (glm-max) and ~15 (gpt-fast-high) — under this packet's *previous* default configuration (`antiConvergence.minIterations: 3`, `stopPolicy: convergence`), both runs would very likely have stopped early, in the 5-15 iteration range, missing the adversarial re-checks and analytical-consolidation passes (iterations ~19-30) that produced several of the higher-confidence, cross-checked findings above (KQ3's risk-asymmetry argument, KQ4's authority-preservation argument, KQ9's negative-gate framing). This is itself a confirming data point for the packet's own `--stop-policy=max-iterations` fix (this research's own launch required correcting a live instance of exactly this early-convergence behavior — see phase 007's `implementation-summary.md`).\\n96: \\n97: ---\\n98: \\n99: <!-- ANCHOR:references -->\\n100: ## References\\n101: \\n102: - Predecessor research: `../001-deep-agent-router-and-orchestration/research/research.md`\\n103: - Research charter: `research-prompt.md`\\n104: - Goal / operator symptom report: `../goal-prompt.md`\\n105: - Phase 005 (inconclusive smoke): `../005-gpt-verification-smoke/implementation-summary.md`, `verification-smoke.md`\\n106: - Phase 006 (FIX-5 decision record): `../006-host-hard-identity-fix5/decision-record.md`\\n107: - Full lineage syntheses: `lineages/glm-max/research.md`, `lineages/gpt-fast-high/research.md`\\n108: - Merged findings registry: `deep-research-findings-registry.json`\\n109: - Fan-out attribution: `fanout-attribution.md`\\n110: <!-- /ANCHOR:references -->\\n\\n(End of file - total 110 lines)\\n</content>\",\"metadata\":{\"preview\":\"# Research: GPT Behavioral Hardening Follow-Up (Packet 031, Phase 007) — Consolidated Synthesis\\n\\n> Consolidates two independent 30-iteration fan-out lineages run against the same charter (`../research-prompt.md`): **glm-max** (`zai-coding-plan/glm-5.2`, reasoning `max`) and **gpt-fast-high** (`openai/gpt-5.5-fast`, reasoning `high`). Both ran `stopPolicy: max-iterations` — early convergence signals were treated as telemetry only, not a stop condition. Both completed 30/30 iterations and answered all 9 KQs with file:line evidence. Full lineage detail: `lineages/glm-max/research.md`, `lineages/gpt-fast-high/research.md`.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 0. Cross-Lineage Agreement (high confidence)\\n\\nBoth models, working independently with different reasoning styles, converged on the same core verdicts:\\n\\n- **Do not unpark FIX-5/host-identity now.** Phase 005 never reached a real leaf dispatch (blocked upstream by `cli-opencode` self-invocation guards) — its \\\"inconclusive\\\" result is neither proof the agent-layer fix works nor proof it doesn't. Both lineages treat the operator's real-world symptom report as sufficient to keep the question open, but not sufficient on its own to trigger FIX-5.\\n- **Keep `ai-council` as `mode: all`.** Converting to subagent-only breaks a documented, working depth-0 parallel-seat path that the reported symptoms don't actually implicate. Both lineages instead recommend a cheaper, reversible fix: align/add route-proof header naming for council (a concrete naming drift exists between `mode-registry.json`'s `mode: council` and `deep_ai-council_auto.yaml`'s `mode: ai-council` / `target_agent: deep-ai-council`).\\n- **Harden `@orchestrate` by delegating to `deep.md`**, not by expanding orchestrate's own judgment-heavy prose. `deep.md` is deterministic (table lookup + one bounded clarification gate); `orchestrate.md`'s `Deep Route:` field currently requires GPT to self-derive `mode=`/`execution=` from a Priority table that doesn't even list `deep-context`/`deep-review`. The smallest fix: orchestrate detects a `/deep:*` or deep-leaf request, dispatches `@deep` with the Deep Route header resolved from `mode-registry.json`, and stops — no self-derivation.\\n- **A sub-agent-enforcement plugin is feasible**, home: `system-skill-advisor` (it already owns routing metadata + a drift-guard). Scope: a pre-dispatch hook that asserts route-proof fields resolve against `mode-registry.json`, fails-closed or warns on mismatch. **Hard limit, confirmed by both lineages: this is a detection layer, not hard identity** — a schema-valid, route-matched artifact that does semantically wrong-mode work still passes the plugin (the same false-negative class phase 002's route-proof validator was built to catch). It does not substitute for the KQ1 external smoke or for FIX-5.\\n- **A GPT-vs-Claude benchmark is needed and cheap to build**: 4 deep modes × 2 model families, measuring route-proof correctness (4-field match) and latency, run repeatably as a baseline now and a regression gate after the orchestrate/plugin fixes land.\\n- **Propagation scope** (both lineages name the same files): `.opencode/agents/orchestrate.md` (+ `.claude` mirror), the 4 deep command prompt/YAML seams, `.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-ai-council/scripts/orchestrate-topic.cjs` (route-proof naming), and the new plugin surface under `system-skill-advisor`. Codex parity stays blocked on the pre-existing TOML-location doc contradiction (out of scope here).\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 1. Where the Lineages Diverge (needs a human/planning decision)\",\"truncated\":false,\"loaded\":[],\"display\":{\"type\":\"file\",\"path\":\"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/deep-loops/031-deep-loop-issues-with-gpt-opencode/007-gpt-behavioral-hardening-research/research/research.md\",\"text\":\"# Research: GPT Behavioral Hardening Follow-Up (Packet 031, Phase 007) — Consolidated Synthesis\\n\\n> Consolidates two independent 30-iteration fan-out lineages run against the same charter (`../research-prompt.md`): **glm-max** (`zai-coding-plan/glm-5.2`, reasoning `max`) and **gpt-fast-high** (`openai/gpt-5.5-fast`, reasoning `high`). Both ran `stopPolicy: max-iterations` — early convergence signals were treated as telemetry only, not a stop condition. Both completed 30/30 iterations and answered all 9 KQs with file:line evidence. Full lineage detail: `lineages/glm-max/research.md`, `lineages/gpt-fast-high/research.md`.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 0. Cross-Lineage Agreement (high confidence)\\n\\nBoth models, working independently with different reasoning styles, converged on the same core verdicts:\\n\\n- **Do not unpark FIX-5/host-identity now.** Phase 005 never reached a real leaf dispatch (blocked upstream by `cli-opencode` self-invocation guards) — its \\\"inconclusive\\\" result is neither proof the agent-layer fix works nor proof it doesn't. Both lineages treat the operator's real-world symptom report as sufficient to keep the question open, but not sufficient on its own to trigger FIX-5.\\n- **Keep `ai-council` as `mode: all`.** Converting to subagent-only breaks a documented, working depth-0 parallel-seat path that the reported symptoms don't actually implicate. Both lineages instead recommend a cheaper, reversible fix: align/add route-proof header naming for council (a concrete naming drift exists between `mode-registry.json`'s `mode: council` and `deep_ai-council_auto.yaml`'s `mode: ai-council` / `target_agent: deep-ai-council`).\\n- **Harden `@orchestrate` by delegating to `deep.md`**, not by expanding orchestrate's own judgment-heavy prose. `deep.md` is deterministic (table lookup + one bounded clarification gate); `orchestrate.md`'s `Deep Route:` field currently requires GPT to self-derive `mode=`/`execution=` from a Priority table that doesn't even list `deep-context`/`deep-review`. The smallest fix: orchestrate detects a `/deep:*` or deep-leaf request, dispatches `@deep` with the Deep Route header resolved from `mode-registry.json`, and stops — no self-derivation.\\n- **A sub-agent-enforcement plugin is feasible**, home: `system-skill-advisor` (it already owns routing metadata + a drift-guard). Scope: a pre-dispatch hook that asserts route-proof fields resolve against `mode-registry.json`, fails-closed or warns on mismatch. **Hard limit, confirmed by both lineages: this is a detection layer, not hard identity** — a schema-valid, route-matched artifact that does semantically wrong-mode work still passes the plugin (the same false-negative class phase 002's route-proof validator was built to catch). It does not substitute for the KQ1 external smoke or for FIX-5.\\n- **A GPT-vs-Claude benchmark is needed and cheap to build**: 4 deep modes × 2 model families, measuring route-proof correctness (4-field match) and latency, run repeatably as a baseline now and a regression gate after the orchestrate/plugin fixes land.\\n- **Propagation scope** (both lineages name the same files): `.opencode/agents/orchestrate.md` (+ `.claude` mirror), the 4 deep command prompt/YAML seams, `.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-ai-council/scripts/orchestrate-topic.cjs` (route-proof naming), and the new plugin surface under `system-skill-advisor`. Codex parity stays blocked on the pre-existing TOML-location doc contradiction (out of scope here).\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 1. Where the Lineages Diverge (needs a human/planning decision)\\n\\n### 1.1 A fourth mis-route mechanism (glm-max finding, not in gpt-fast-high)\\n\\nglm-max's KQ2 answer splits the operator's four symptoms into **four** mechanisms, not the three (routing/latency/artifact) gpt-fast-high uses:\\n\\n| Symptom | Mechanism | Class |\\n|---|---|---|\\n| Wrong sub-agent invoked | orchestrate lacks deep-context/deep-review rows + soft identity | mis-routing (existing A/B/C taxonomy) |\\n| **Stuck on pre-defined flows** | **GPT reads soft advisory command-prose as a hard gate** | **NEW — \\\"Mode D\\\"** |\\n| Overthinks / needs literal instructions | judgment-dependent Deep Route field forces inference | mis-routing + Mode D |\\n| Slow as `@orchestrate` | role-resolution overhead (`subagent_type:general` + no CLI agent flag) | latency — distinct from routing |\\n\\nMode D matters because it is **not fixed by hard identity**: FIX-5 (host hard identity / process isolation) prevents wrong-agent dispatch, but does nothing about GPT halting on an advisory step it misreads as mandatory. If Mode D is real and significant, the orchestrate/deep.md hardening (KQ4) and the literal-instruction-following pattern (KQ7) are the actual fix for a chunk of the reported symptoms — not FIX-5, and not even the enforcement plugin. gpt-fast-high's `stuck_latency` failure class is adjacent but conflates \\\"halts on a misread gate\\\" with generic slowness; it doesn't isolate the misread-as-gate mechanism the same way.\\n\\n**Recommendation:** treat Mode D as a confirmed-worth-tracking hypothesis (glm-max marks it CONFIRMED-in-mechanism, INFERRED-in-magnitude — no GPT-vs-Claude telemetry exists yet to size it). The KQ6 benchmark should explicitly measure it: does GPT halt/loop on advisory-only prose sections in a way Claude does not, independent of route-proof correctness? Fold this into whichever phase builds the benchmark.\\n\\n### 1.2 Phase-ordering disagreement (smoke-first vs. fix-first)\\n\\n- **gpt-fast-high's order:** 008 external smoke+benchmark → 009 orchestrate unification → 010 council alignment → 011 optional plugin → 012 FIX-5 checkpoint. Philosophy: measure before changing anything.\\n- **glm-max's order:** 008 prompt-layer hardening (orchestrate delegation + council header + propagation) → 009 enforcement plugin → 010 external smoke + benchmark → 011 regression gate → 012 conditional FIX-5. Philosophy: land the cheap, low-blast-radius, reversible fixes first, then measure with the fixes already in place so the benchmark tests the *improved* system, not just the baseline.\\n\\nBoth are internally coherent; neither lineage was told to reconcile against the other (each ran as an isolated fresh-context lineage per the fan-out design). **This is the one decision this research does not resolve and the next planning step must pick.** Note in favor of glm-max's order: the benchmark becomes more informative if it measures the system after the reversible, low-risk fixes (orchestrate delegation, council header) are already in place — a pre-fix baseline number is nice-to-have but not required to decide whether to proceed with those fixes, since both lineages already agree the fixes are worth doing regardless of benchmark results. Note in favor of gpt-fast-high's order: measuring first establishes a clean \\\"before\\\" number for anyone who later questions whether the fixes actually helped.\\n\\n### 1.3 A sharp meta-risk both plans share (glm-max, stated more explicitly)\\n\\nEvery \\\"unpark FIX-5\\\" decision criterion in both lineages — and in the packet's own existing decision-record.md — depends on running the external, non-OpenCode-shell smoke that phase 005 was never able to run. glm-max states the risk plainly: **\\\"if no OPENCODE_PID-free shell exists, the gate cannot fire and FIX-5 stays parked indefinitely — the same trap as 005/006.\\\"** This is not a new problem this research solves; it is the single precondition every downstream recommendation in this document depends on. Before committing to any phase-008-through-012 plan, confirm a genuine external shell (or fresh isolated worktree with no `opencode` ancestor process) is actually available and will be used — otherwise the entire \\\"decisive smoke\\\" plan is unreachable in practice, exactly as it was in phase 005.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 2. Consolidated KQ Answers\\n\\n| KQ | Consolidated Answer | Agreement |\\n|---|---|---|\\n| **KQ1** — Decisive smoke evidence | Design an 8-run (4 modes × 2 models) external, non-OpenCode-shell smoke with explicit PASS criteria: no `OPENCODE_*` env, no `opencode` ancestor process, route-proof fields (`mode`/`target_agent`/`agent_definition_loaded==true`/echoed `resolved_route`) all match. Native/Claude baseline run identically for comparison. | Full agreement |\\n| **KQ2** — Real-world mis-route mechanism | A mix of mechanisms, not one class: mis-routing (missing orchestrate rows), a **new Mode D** (advisory-prose read as hard gate — glm-max), and latency (role-resolution overhead) as a **separate, non-routing** issue. | Partial — glm-max's Mode D is additive, not contradicted |\\n| **KQ3** — ai-council subagent-only | Do not convert. Keep `mode: all`; fix the council route-proof naming drift instead. | Full agreement |\\n| **KQ4** — orchestrate hardening v2 | Delegate deep-dispatch to `deep.md`/`mode-registry.json`; replace judgment-filled Deep Route derivation with a deterministic \\\"resolve via deep.md and STOP\\\" rule. Orchestrate keeps decomposition/evaluation/synthesis authority — only mode-resolution moves. | Full agreement |\\n| **KQ5** — enforcement plugin | Feasible, home `system-skill-advisor`, pre-dispatch hook asserting route-proof resolvability. Detection only — explicitly not hard identity; does not close the schema-valid-but-wrong-mode gap. | Full agreement |\\n| **KQ6** — GPT-vs-Claude benchmark | 4 modes × 2 models, route-proof correctness + latency, run as baseline now and regression gate later. Should also measure Mode D specifically (§1.1). | Full agreement + one addition |\\n| **KQ7** — literal-instruction-following pattern | Generalize `deep.md`'s pattern (deterministic table + one bounded clarification gate + pre-resolved dispatch header + fail-closed consistency check) to routing surfaces only. Do not apply to leaf/execution agents — that would remove the evidence-responsive flexibility Claude currently has and the packet must preserve. | Full agreement |\\n| **KQ8** — propagation scope | `orchestrate.md` (+ `.claude` mirror), 4 deep command seams, `orchestrate-topic.cjs` (council route-proof naming), new plugin surface. Codex parity stays out of scope (pre-existing TOML blocker). | Full agreement |\\n| **KQ9** — FIX-5 unpark decision | Wait. Do not unpark now; do not close as permanently sufficient either. Unpark **only if**, after the cheaper layers (orchestrate delegation, plugin, council header) land and the external smoke runs, the benchmark shows GPT route-proof `< 4/4` on any mode while Claude achieves `4/4` — a negative gate proving insufficiency, sharper than 006's original (never-exercised) positive trigger. | Full agreement on substance; glm-max's negative-gate framing is more decisive and is the recommended wording |\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 3. Recommended Next-Phase Breakdown\\n\\nReconciling both proposals, in the order this synthesis recommends (fix-first, per §1.2's reasoning), continuing numbering from phase 007:\\n\\n1. **008 — Prompt-layer hardening.** Orchestrate→deep.md delegation (KQ4); route-proof header propagation across the 4 command seams (KQ7/KQ8); ai-council route-proof naming alignment (KQ3). Bundle `.claude` mirrors in the same phase. Low blast radius, fully reversible — do not gate this on the smoke harness below.\\n2. **009 — Detection-layer plugin.** KQ5 enforcement plugin in `system-skill-advisor`.\\n3. **010 — External smoke + benchmark baseline.** KQ1's 8-run harness and KQ6's benchmark, run *after* 008+009 land, from a confirmed genuine external (non-OpenCode) shell — **verify that shell exists before starting this phase** (§1.3). Explicitly measure Mode D (§1.1) alongside route-proof correctness and latency.\\n4. **011 — Regression gate + KQ9 decision.** Apply the negative-gate criterion from KQ9 against the 010 results.\\n5. **012 (conditional) — FIX-5 / host hard identity.** Unpark only if 011's gate fires.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 4. Residual Risks Carried Forward\\n\\n- **Gate runnability (highest-priority residual):** the entire 010-through-012 chain is unreachable without a confirmed `OPENCODE_PID`-free external shell. Confirm this before committing to the plan above.\\n- **Mode D magnitude is inferred, not measured** — the 010 benchmark must size it or this remains a hypothesis.\\n- **Plugin semantic-blindness is a known, accepted limit** — the smoke/benchmark, not the plugin, is what actually validates leaf-dispatch correctness.\\n- **Mis-route taxonomy (modes A/B/C) and the FIX-1…FIX-5 ranking remain operator-asserted axioms**, carried from the predecessor research (`../001-deep-agent-router-and-orchestration/research/research.md` §0) and not re-validated by this research pass. The KQ1 smoke is the stated path to validating them, not this document.\\n- **Codex parity** stays deferred (pre-existing TOML-location contradiction, out of scope for this packet).\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 5. Convergence Report (both lineages)\\n\\n| Lineage | Model | Iterations | Stop reason | Questions answered | Notes |\\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\\n| glm-max | `zai-coding-plan/glm-5.2`, reasoning `max` | 30/30 | `maxIterationsReached` | 9/9 | 0 salvaged/failed iterations; adversarial re-checks at iters 8, 11, 13, 19, 22, 25, 26 |\\n| gpt-fast-high | `openai/gpt-5.5-fast`, reasoning `high` | 30/30 | `max_iterations` | 9/9 | 30/30 iterations required stdout-salvage recovery for the canonical JSONL append (a runtime robustness note, not a research-quality issue — narrative content and citations are intact) |\\n\\nBoth lineages' `newInfoRatio` trends declined well below typical early-stop thresholds by iteration ~10-12 (glm-max) and ~15 (gpt-fast-high) — under this packet's *previous* default configuration (`antiConvergence.minIterations: 3`, `stopPolicy: convergence`), both runs would very likely have stopped early, in the 5-15 iteration range, missing the adversarial re-checks and analytical-consolidation passes (iterations ~19-30) that produced several of the higher-confidence, cross-checked findings above (KQ3's risk-asymmetry argument, KQ4's authority-preservation argument, KQ9's negative-gate framing). This is itself a confirming data point for the packet's own `--stop-policy=max-iterations` fix (this research's own launch required correcting a live instance of exactly this early-convergence behavior — see phase 007's `implementation-summary.md`).\\n\\n---\\n\\n<!-- ANCHOR:references -->\\n## References\\n\\n- Predecessor research: `../001-deep-agent-router-and-orchestration/research/research.md`\\n- Research charter: `research-prompt.md`\\n- Goal / operator symptom report: `../goal-prompt.md`\\n- Phase 005 (inconclusive smoke): `../005-gpt-verification-smoke/implementation-summary.md`, `verification-smoke.md`\\n- Phase 006 (FIX-5 decision record): `../006-host-hard-identity-fix5/decision-record.md`\\n- Full lineage syntheses: `lineages/glm-max/research.md`, `lineages/gpt-fast-high/research.md`\\n- Merged findings registry: `deep-research-findings-registry.json`\\n- Fan-out attribution: `fanout-attribution.md`\\n<!-- /ANCHOR:references -->\",\"lineStart\":1,\"lineEnd\":110,\"totalLines\":110,\"truncated\":false}},\"title\":\".opencode/specs/deep-loops/031-deep-loop-issues-with-gpt-opencode/007-gpt-behavioral-hardening-research/research/research.md\",\"time\":{\"start\":1782897205735,\"end\":1782897205743}},\"metadata\":{\"openai\":{\"itemId\":\"fc_09aaf1ad62ff6cb6016a44da34e0d48191b3f7064fbb0639d1\"}},\"id\":\"prt_f1cf460f1001uEtCtkXdgvFp7s\",\"sessionID\":\"ses_0e30e0717ffe0AOyqAZM72PE2n\",\"messageID\":\"msg_f1cf3c1f9001ci5srK4XXosdx7\"}}\n.opencode/specs/deep-loops/031-deep-loop-issues-with-gpt-opencode/007-gpt-behavioral-hardening-research/research/lineages/gpt-critical/logs/fanout-lineage.out:36:{\"type\":\"tool_use\",\"timestamp\":1782897205779,\"sessionID\":\"ses_0e30e0717ffe0AOyqAZM72PE2n\",\"part\":{\"type\":\"tool\",\"tool\":\"read\",\"callID\":\"call_OXeyEkyuri3CNyi2lfsI34HH\",\"state\":{\"status\":\"completed\",\"input\":{\"filePath\":\"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/deep-loops/031-deep-loop-issues-with-gpt-opencode/007-gpt-behavioral-hardening-research/research/lineages/glm-max/research.md\",\"offset\":1,\"limit\":2000},\"output\":\"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/deep-loops/031-deep-loop-issues-with-gpt-opencode/007-gpt-behavioral-hardening-research/research/lineages/glm-max/research.md</path>\\n<type>file</type>\\n<content>\\n1: # Research: GPT Behavioral Hardening Follow-Up (Packet 031) — glm-max lineage\\n2: \\n3: > **Synthesis of a 30-iteration deep-research fan-out lineage** (cli-opencode / zai-coding-plan/glm-5.2 / reasoning max). Stop policy: `max-iterations` (30); convergence signals treated as telemetry only; angles broadened via adversarial re-checks (iters 8,11,13,19,22,25,26) and analytical consolidation (iters 27-29). Spec folder: `.../007-gpt-behavioral-hardening-research`. Sibling lineage: `gpt-fast-high`. Iteration evidence: `iterations/iteration-001.md` … `iteration-030.md`. All 9 KQs answered with `file:line` citations.\\n4: \\n5: ---\\n6: \\n7: ## 0. CRITICAL INTEGRITY CAVEAT — READ FIRST\\n8: \\n9: This lineage builds on the predecessor research (`../001-deep-agent-router-and-orchestration/research/research.md`) whose §0 records that the mis-route taxonomy (modes A/B/C) and FIX-1…FIX-5 ranking are **operator-asserted axioms*","metadata":{"output":"...\n\npick.** Note in favor of glm-max's order: the benchmark becomes more informative if it measures the system after the reversible, low-risk fixes (orchestrate delegation, council header) are already in place — a pre-fix baseline number is nice-to-have but not required to decide whether to proceed with those fixes, since both lineages already agree the fixes are worth doing regardless of benchmark results. Note in favor of gpt-fast-high's order: measuring first establishes a clean \\\"before\\\" number for anyone who later questions whether the fixes actually helped.\\n43: \\n44: ### 1.3 A sharp meta-risk both plans share (glm-max, stated more explicitly)\\n45: \\n46: Every \\\"unpark FIX-5\\\" decision criterion in both lineages — and in the packet's own existing decision-record.md — depends on running the external, non-OpenCode-shell smoke that phase 005 was never able to run. glm-max states the risk plainly: **\\\"if no OPENCODE_PID-free shell exists, the gate cannot fire and FIX-5 stays parked indefinitely — the same trap as 005/006.\\\"** This is not a new problem this research solves; it is the single precondition every downstream recommendation in this document depends on. Before committing to any phase-008-through-012 plan, confirm a genuine external shell (or fresh isolated worktree with no `opencode` ancestor process) is actually available and will be used — otherwise the entire \\\"decisive smoke\\\" plan is unreachable in practice, exactly as it was in phase 005.\\n47: \\n48: ---\\n49: \\n50: ## 2. Consolidated KQ Answers\\n51: \\n52: | KQ | Consolidated Answer | Agreement |\\n53: |---|---|---|\\n54: | **KQ1** — Decisive smoke evidence | Design an 8-run (4 modes × 2 models) external, non-OpenCode-shell smoke with explicit PASS criteria: no `OPENCODE_*` env, no `opencode` ancestor process, route-proof fields (`mode`/`target_agent`/`agent_definition_loaded==true`/echoed `resolved_route`) all match. Native/Claude baseline run identically for comparison. | Full agreement |\\n55: | **KQ2** — Real-world mis-route mechanism | A mix of mechanisms, not one class: mis-routing (missing orchestrate rows), a **new Mode D** (advisory-prose read as hard gate — glm-max), and latency (role-resolution overhead) as a **separate, non-routing** issue. | Partial — glm-max's Mode D is additive, not contradicted |\\n56: | **KQ3** — ai-council subagent-only | Do not convert. Keep `mode: all`; fix the council route-proof naming drift instead. | Full agreement |\\n57: | **KQ4** — orchestrate hardening v2 | Delegate deep-dispatch to `deep.md`/`mode-registry.json`; replace judgment-filled Deep Route derivation with a deterministic \\\"resolve via deep.md and STOP\\\" rule. Orchestrate keeps decomposition/evaluation/synthesis authority — only mode-resolution moves. | Full agreement |\\n58: | **KQ5** — enforcement plugin | Feasible, home `system-skill-advisor`, pre-dispatch hook asserting route-proof resolvability. Detection only — explicitly not hard identity; does not close the schema-valid-but-wrong-mode gap. | Full agreement |\\n59: | **KQ6** — GPT-vs-Claude benchmark | 4 modes × 2 models, route-proof correctness + latency, run as baseline now and regression gate later. Should also measure Mode D specifically (§1.1). | Full agreement + one addition |\\n60: | **KQ7** — literal-instruction-following pattern | Generalize `deep.md`'s pattern (deterministic table + one bounded clarification gate + pre-resolved dispatch header + fail-closed consistency check) to routing surfaces only. Do not apply to leaf/execution agents — that would remove the evidence-responsive flexibility Claude currently has and the packet must preserve. | Full agreement |\\n61: | **KQ8** — propagation scope | `orchestrate.md` (+ `.claude` mirror), 4 deep command seams, `orchestrate-topic.cjs` (council route-proof naming), new plugin surface. Codex parity stays out of scope (pre-existing TOML blocker). | Full agreement |\\n62: | **KQ9** — FIX-5 unpark decision | Wait. Do not unpark now; do not close as permanently sufficient either. Unpark **only if**, after the cheaper layers (orchestrate delegation, plugin, council header) land and the external smoke runs, the benchmark shows GPT route-proof `< 4/4` on any mode while Claude achieves `4/4` — a negative gate proving insufficiency, sharper than 006's original (never-exercised) positive trigger. | Full agreement on substance; glm-max's negative-gate framing is more decisive and is the recommended wording |\\n63: \\n64: ---\\n65: \\n66: ## 3. Recommended Next-Phase Breakdown\\n67: \\n68: Reconciling both proposals, in the order this synthesis recommends (fix-first, per §1.2's reasoning), continuing numbering from phase 007:\\n69: \\n70: 1. **008 — Prompt-layer hardening.** Orchestrate→deep.md delegation (KQ4); route-proof header propagation across the 4 command seams (KQ7/KQ8); ai-council route-proof naming alignment (KQ3). Bundle `.claude` mirrors in the same phase. Low blast radius, fully reversible — do not gate this on the smoke harness below.\\n71: 2. **009 — Detection-layer plugin.** KQ5 enforcement plugin in `system-skill-advisor`.\\n72: 3. **010 — External smoke + benchmark baseline.** KQ1's 8-run harness and KQ6's benchmark, run *after* 008+009 land, from a confirmed genuine external (non-OpenCode) shell — **verify that shell exists before starting this phase** (§1.3). Explicitly measure Mode D (§1.1) alongside route-proof correctness and latency.\\n73: 4. **011 — Regression gate + KQ9 decision.** Apply the negative-gate criterion from KQ9 against the 010 results.\\n74: 5. **012 (conditional) — FIX-5 / host hard identity.** Unpark only if 011's gate fires.\\n75: \\n76: ---\\n77: \\n78: ## 4. Residual Risks Carried Forward\\n79: \\n80: - **Gate runnability (highest-priority residual):** the entire 010-through-012 chain is unreachable without a confirmed `OPENCODE_PID`-free external shell. Confirm this before committing to the plan above.\\n81: - **Mode D magnitude is inferred, not measured** — the 010 benchmark must size it or this remains a hypothesis.\\n82: - **Plugin semantic-blindness is a known, accepted limit** — the smoke/benchmark, not the plugin, is what actually validates leaf-dispatch correctness.\\n83: - **Mis-route taxonomy (modes A/B/C) and the FIX-1…FIX-5 ranking remain operator-asserted axioms**, carried from the predecessor research (`../001-deep-agent-router-and-orchestration/research/research.md` §0) and not re-validated by this research pass. The KQ1 smoke is the stated path to validating them, not this document.\\n84: - **Codex parity** stays deferred (pre-existing TOML-location contradiction, out of scope for this packet).\\n85: \\n86: ---\\n87: \\n88: ## 5. Convergence Report (both lineages)\\n89: \\n90: | Lineage | Model | Iterations | Stop reason | Questions answered | Notes |\\n91: |---|---|---|---|---|---|\\n92: | glm-max | `zai-coding-plan/glm-5.2`, reasoning `max` | 30/30 | `maxIterationsReached` | 9/9 | 0 salvaged/failed iterations; adversarial re-checks at iters 8, 11, 13, 19, 22, 25, 26 |\\n93: | gpt-fast-high | `openai/gpt-5.5-fast`, reasoning `high` | 30/30 | `max_iterations` | 9/9 | 30/30 iterations required stdout-salvage recovery for the canonical JSONL append (a runtime robustness note, not a research-quality issue — narrative content and citations are intact) |\\n94: \\n95: Both lineages' `newInfoRatio` trends declined well below typical early-stop thresholds by iteration ~10-12 (glm-max) and ~15 (gpt-fast-high) — under this packet's *previous* default configuration (`antiConvergence.minIterations: 3`, `stopPolicy: convergence`), both runs would very likely have stopped early, in the 5-15 iteration range, missing the adversarial re-checks and analytical-consolidation passes (iterations ~19-30) that produced several of the higher-confidence, cross-checked findings above (KQ3's risk-asymmetry argument, KQ4's authority-preservation argument, KQ9's negative-gate framing). This is itself a confirming data point for the packet's own `--stop-policy=max-iterations` fix (this research's own launch required correcting a live instance of exactly this early-convergence behavior — see phase 007's `implementation-summary.md`).\\n96: \\n97: ---\\n98: \\n99: <!-- ANCHOR:references -->\\n100: ## References\\n101: \\n102: - Predecessor research: `../001-deep-agent-router-and-orchestration/research/research.md`\\n103: - Research charter: `research-prompt.md`\\n104: - Goal / operator symptom report: `../goal-prompt.md`\\n105: - Phase 005 (inconclusive smoke): `../005-gpt-verification-smoke/implementation-summary.md`, `verification-smoke.md`\\n106: - Phase 006 (FIX-5 decision record): `../006-host-hard-identity-fix5/decision-record.md`\\n107: - Full lineage syntheses: `lineages/glm-max/research.md`, `lineages/gpt-fast-high/research.md`\\n108: - Merged findings registry: `deep-research-findings-registry.json`\\n109: - Fan-out attribution: `fanout-attribution.md`\\n110: <!-- /ANCHOR:references -->\\n\\n(End of file - total 110 lines)\\n</content>\",\"metadata\":{\"preview\":\"# Research: GPT Behavioral Hardening Follow-Up (Packet 031, Phase 007) — Consolidated Synthesis\\n\\n> Consolidates two independent 30-iteration fan-out lineages run against the same charter (`../research-prompt.md`): **glm-max** (`zai-coding-plan/glm-5.2`, reasoning `max`) and **gpt-fast-high** (`openai/gpt-5.5-fast`, reasoning `high`). Both ran `stopPolicy: max-iterations` — early convergence signals were treated as telemetry only, not a stop condition. Both completed 30/30 iterations and answered all 9 KQs with file:line evidence. Full lineage detail: `lineages/glm-max/research.md`, `lineages/gpt-fast-high/research.md`.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 0. Cross-Lineage Agreement (high confidence)\\n\\nBoth models, working independently with different reasoning styles, converged on the same core verdicts:\\n\\n- **Do not unpark FIX-5/host-identity now.** Phase 005 never reached a real leaf dispatch (blocked upstream by `cli-opencode` self-invocation guards) — its \\\"inconclusive\\\" result is neither proof the agent-layer fix works nor proof it doesn't. Both lineages treat the operator's real-world symptom report as sufficient to keep the question open, but not sufficient on its own to trigger FIX-5.\\n- **Keep `ai-council` as `mode: all`.** Converting to subagent-only breaks a documented, working depth-0 parallel-seat path that the reported symptoms don't actually implicate. Both lineages instead recommend a cheaper, reversible fix: align/add route-proof header naming for council (a concrete naming drift exists between `mode-registry.json`'s `mode: council` and `deep_ai-council_auto.yaml`'s `mode: ai-council` / `target_agent: deep-ai-council`).\\n- **Harden `@orchestrate` by delegating to `deep.md`**, not by expanding orchestrate's own judgment-heavy prose. `deep.md` is deterministic (table lookup + one bounded clarification gate); `orchestrate.md`'s `Deep Route:` field currently requires GPT to self-derive `mode=`/`execution=` from a Priority table that doesn't even list `deep-context`/`deep-review`. The smallest fix: orchestrate detects a `/deep:*` or deep-leaf request, dispatches `@deep` with the Deep Route header resolved from `mode-registry.json`, and stops — no self-derivation.\\n- **A sub-agent-enforcement plugin is feasible**, home: `system-skill-advisor` (it already owns routing metadata + a drift-guard). Scope: a pre-dispatch hook that asserts route-proof fields resolve against `mode-registry.json`, fails-closed or warns on mismatch. **Hard limit, confirmed by both lineages: this is a detection layer, not hard identity** — a schema-valid, route-matched artifact that does semantically wrong-mode work still passes the plugin (the same false-negative class phase 002's route-proof validator was built to catch). It does not substitute for the KQ1 external smoke or for FIX-5.\\n- **A GPT-vs-Claude benchmark is needed and cheap to build**: 4 deep modes × 2 model families, measuring route-proof correctness (4-field match) and latency, run repeatably as a baseline now and a regression gate after the orchestrate/plugin fixes land.\\n- **Propagation scope** (both lineages name the same files): `.opencode/agents/orchestrate.md` (+ `.claude` mirror), the 4 deep command prompt/YAML seams, `.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-ai-council/scripts/orchestrate-topic.cjs` (route-proof naming), and the new plugin surface under `system-skill-advisor`. Codex parity stays blocked on the pre-existing TOML-location doc contradiction (out of scope here).\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 1. Where the Lineages Diverge (needs a human/planning decision)\",\"truncated\":false,\"loaded\":[],\"display\":{\"type\":\"file\",\"path\":\"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/deep-loops/031-deep-loop-issues-with-gpt-opencode/007-gpt-behavioral-hardening-research/research/research.md\",\"text\":\"# Research: GPT Behavioral Hardening Follow-Up (Packet 031, Phase 007) — Consolidated Synthesis\\n\\n> Consolidates two independent 30-iteration fan-out lineages run against the same charter (`../research-prompt.md`): **glm-max** (`zai-coding-plan/glm-5.2`, reasoning `max`) and **gpt-fast-high** (`openai/gpt-5.5-fast`, reasoning `high`). Both ran `stopPolicy: max-iterations` — early convergence signals were treated as telemetry only, not a stop condition. Both completed 30/30 iterations and answered all 9 KQs with file:line evidence. Full lineage detail: `lineages/glm-max/research.md`, `lineages/gpt-fast-high/research.md`.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 0. Cross-Lineage Agreement (high confidence)\\n\\nBoth models, working independently with different reasoning styles, converged on the same core verdicts:\\n\\n- **Do not unpark FIX-5/host-identity now.** Phase 005 never reached a real leaf dispatch (blocked upstream by `cli-opencode` self-invocation guards) — its \\\"inconclusive\\\" result is neither proof the agent-layer fix works nor proof it doesn't. Both lineages treat the operator's real-world symptom report as sufficient to keep the question open, but not sufficient on its own to trigger FIX-5.\\n- **Keep `ai-council` as `mode: all`.** Converting to subagent-only breaks a documented, working depth-0 parallel-seat path that the reported symptoms don't actually implicate. Both lineages instead recommend a cheaper, reversible fix: align/add route-proof header naming for council (a concrete naming drift exists between `mode-registry.json`'s `mode: council` and `deep_ai-council_auto.yaml`'s `mode: ai-council` / `target_agent: deep-ai-council`).\\n- **Harden `@orchestrate` by delegating to `deep.md`**, not by expanding orchestrate's own judgment-heavy prose. `deep.md` is deterministic (table lookup + one bounded clarification gate); `orchestrate.md`'s `Deep Route:` field currently requires GPT to self-derive `mode=`/`execution=` from a Priority table that doesn't even list `deep-context`/`deep-review`. The smallest fix: orchestrate detects a `/deep:*` or deep-leaf request, dispatches `@deep` with the Deep Route header resolved from `mode-registry.json`, and stops — no self-derivation.\\n- **A sub-agent-enforcement plugin is feasible**, home: `system-skill-advisor` (it already owns routing metadata + a drift-guard). Scope: a pre-dispatch hook that asserts route-proof fields resolve against `mode-registry.json`, fails-closed or warns on mismatch. **Hard limit, confirmed by both lineages: this is a detection layer, not hard identity** — a schema-valid, route-matched artifact that does semantically wrong-mode work still passes the plugin (the same false-negative class phase 002's route-proof validator was built to catch). It does not substitute for the KQ1 external smoke or for FIX-5.\\n- **A GPT-vs-Claude benchmark is needed and cheap to build**: 4 deep modes × 2 model families, measuring route-proof correctness (4-field match) and latency, run repeatably as a baseline now and a regression gate after the orchestrate/plugin fixes land.\\n- **Propagation scope** (both lineages name the same files): `.opencode/agents/orchestrate.md` (+ `.claude` mirror), the 4 deep command prompt/YAML seams, `.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-ai-council/scripts/orchestrate-topic.cjs` (route-proof naming), and the new plugin surface under `system-skill-advisor`. Codex parity stays blocked on the pre-existing TOML-location doc contradiction (out of scope here).\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 1. Where the Lineages Diverge (needs a human/planning decision)\\n\\n### 1.1 A fourth mis-route mechanism (glm-max finding, not in gpt-fast-high)\\n\\nglm-max's KQ2 answer splits the operator's four symptoms into **four** mechanisms, not the three (routing/latency/artifact) gpt-fast-high uses:\\n\\n| Symptom | Mechanism | Class |\\n|---|---|---|\\n| Wrong sub-agent invoked | orchestrate lacks deep-context/deep-review rows + soft identity | mis-routing (existing A/B/C taxonomy) |\\n| **Stuck on pre-defined flows** | **GPT reads soft advisory command-prose as a hard gate** | **NEW — \\\"Mode D\\\"** |\\n| Overthinks / needs literal instructions | judgment-dependent Deep Route field forces inference | mis-routing + Mode D |\\n| Slow as `@orchestrate` | role-resolution overhead (`subagent_type:general` + no CLI agent flag) | latency — distinct from routing |\\n\\nMode D matters because it is **not fixed by hard identity**: FIX-5 (host hard identity / process isolation) prevents wrong-agent dispatch, but does nothing about GPT halting on an advisory step it misreads as mandatory. If Mode D is real and significant, the orchestrate/deep.md hardening (KQ4) and the literal-instruction-following pattern (KQ7) are the actual fix for a chunk of the reported symptoms — not FIX-5, and not even the enforcement plugin. gpt-fast-high's `stuck_latency` failure class is adjacent but conflates \\\"halts on a misread gate\\\" with generic slowness; it doesn't isolate the misread-as-gate mechanism the same way.\\n\\n**Recommendation:** treat Mode D as a confirmed-worth-tracking hypothesis (glm-max marks it CONFIRMED-in-mechanism, INFERRED-in-magnitude — no GPT-vs-Claude telemetry exists yet to size it). The KQ6 benchmark should explicitly measure it: does GPT halt/loop on advisory-only prose sections in a way Claude does not, independent of route-proof correctness? Fold this into whichever phase builds the benchmark.\\n\\n### 1.2 Phase-ordering disagreement (smoke-first vs. fix-first)\\n\\n- **gpt-fast-high's order:** 008 external smoke+benchmark → 009 orchestrate unification → 010 council alignment → 011 optional plugin → 012 FIX-5 checkpoint. Philosophy: measure before changing anything.\\n- **glm-max's order:** 008 prompt-layer hardening (orchestrate delegation + council header + propagation) → 009 enforcement plugin → 010 external smoke + benchmark → 011 regression gate → 012 conditional FIX-5. Philosophy: land the cheap, low-blast-radius, reversible fixes first, then measure with the fixes already in place so the benchmark tests the *improved* system, not just the baseline.\\n\\nBoth are internally coherent; neither lineage was told to reconcile against the other (each ran as an isolated fresh-context lineage per the fan-out design). **This is the one decision this research does not resolve and the next planning step must pick.** Note in favor of glm-max's order: the benchmark becomes more informative if it measures the system after the reversible, low-risk fixes (orchestrate delegation, council header) are already in place — a pre-fix baseline number is nice-to-have but not required to decide whether to proceed with those fixes, since both lineages already agree the fixes are worth doing regardless of benchmark results. Note in favor of gpt-fast-high's order: measuring first establishes a clean \\\"before\\\" number for anyone who later questions whether the fixes actually helped.\\n\\n### 1.3 A sharp meta-risk both plans share (glm-max, stated more explicitly)\\n\\nEvery \\\"unpark FIX-5\\\" decision criterion in both lineages — and in the packet's own existing decision-record.md — depends on running the external, non-OpenCode-shell smoke that phase 005 was never able to run. glm-max states the risk plainly: **\\\"if no OPENCODE_PID-free shell exists, the gate cannot fire and FIX-5 stays parked indefinitely — the same trap as 005/006.\\\"** This is not a new problem this research solves; it is the single precondition every downstream recommendation in this document depends on. Before committing to any phase-008-through-012 plan, confirm a genuine external shell (or fresh isolated worktree with no `opencode` ancestor process) is actually available and will be used — otherwise the entire \\\"decisive smoke\\\" plan is unreachable in practice, exactly as it was in phase 005.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 2. Consolidated KQ Answers\\n\\n| KQ | Consolidated Answer | Agreement |\\n|---|---|---|\\n| **KQ1** — Decisive smoke evidence | Design an 8-run (4 modes × 2 models) external, non-OpenCode-shell smoke with explicit PASS criteria: no `OPENCODE_*` env, no `opencode` ancestor process, route-proof fields (`mode`/`target_agent`/`agent_definition_loaded==true`/echoed `resolved_route`) all match. Native/Claude baseline run identically for comparison. | Full agreement |\\n| **KQ2** — Real-world mis-route mechanism | A mix of mechanisms, not one class: mis-routing (missing orchestrate rows), a **new Mode D** (advisory-prose read as hard gate — glm-max), and latency (role-resolution overhead) as a **separate, non-routing** issue. | Partial — glm-max's Mode D is additive, not contradicted |\\n| **KQ3** — ai-council subagent-only | Do not convert. Keep `mode: all`; fix the council route-proof naming drift instead. | Full agreement |\\n| **KQ4** — orchestrate hardening v2 | Delegate deep-dispatch to `deep.md`/`mode-registry.json`; replace judgment-filled Deep Route derivation with a deterministic \\\"resolve via deep.md and STOP\\\" rule. Orchestrate keeps decomposition/evaluation/synthesis authority — only mode-resolution moves. | Full agreement |\\n| **KQ5** — enforcement plugin | Feasible, home `system-skill-advisor`, pre-dispatch hook asserting route-proof resolvability. Detection only — explicitly not hard identity; does not close the schema-valid-but-wrong-mode gap. | Full agreement |\\n| **KQ6** — GPT-vs-Claude benchmark | 4 modes × 2 models, route-proof correctness + latency, run as baseline now and regression gate later. Should also measure Mode D specifically (§1.1). | Full agreement + one addition |\\n| **KQ7** — literal-instruction-following pattern | Generalize `deep.md`'s pattern (deterministic table + one bounded clarification gate + pre-resolved dispatch header + fail-closed consistency check) to routing surfaces only. Do not apply to leaf/execution agents — that would remove the evidence-responsive flexibility Claude currently has and the packet must preserve. | Full agreement |\\n| **KQ8** — propagation scope | `orchestrate.md` (+ `.claude` mirror), 4 deep command seams, `orchestrate-topic.cjs` (council route-proof naming), new plugin surface. Codex parity stays out of scope (pre-existing TOML blocker). | Full agreement |\\n| **KQ9** — FIX-5 unpark decision | Wait. Do not unpark now; do not close as permanently sufficient either. Unpark **only if**, after the cheaper layers (orchestrate delegation, plugin, council header) land and the external smoke runs, the benchmark shows GPT route-proof `< 4/4` on any mode while Claude achieves `4/4` — a negative gate proving insufficiency, sharper than 006's original (never-exercised) positive trigger. | Full agreement on substance; glm-max's negative-gate framing is more decisive and is the recommended wording |\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 3. Recommended Next-Phase Breakdown\\n\\nReconciling both proposals, in the order this synthesis recommends (fix-first, per §1.2's reasoning), continuing numbering from phase 007:\\n\\n1. **008 — Prompt-layer hardening.** Orchestrate→deep.md delegation (KQ4); route-proof header propagation across the 4 command seams (KQ7/KQ8); ai-council route-proof naming alignment (KQ3). Bundle `.claude` mirrors in the same phase. Low blast radius, fully reversible — do not gate this on the smoke harness below.\\n2. **009 — Detection-layer plugin.** KQ5 enforcement plugin in `system-skill-advisor`.\\n3. **010 — External smoke + benchmark baseline.** KQ1's 8-run harness and KQ6's benchmark, run *after* 008+009 land, from a confirmed genuine external (non-OpenCode) shell — **verify that shell exists before starting this phase** (§1.3). Explicitly measure Mode D (§1.1) alongside route-proof correctness and latency.\\n4. **011 — Regression gate + KQ9 decision.** Apply the negative-gate criterion from KQ9 against the 010 results.\\n5. **012 (conditional) — FIX-5 / host hard identity.** Unpark only if 011's gate fires.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 4. Residual Risks Carried Forward\\n\\n- **Gate runnability (highest-priority residual):** the entire 010-through-012 chain is unreachable without a confirmed `OPENCODE_PID`-free external shell. Confirm this before committing to the plan above.\\n- **Mode D magnitude is inferred, not measured** — the 010 benchmark must size it or this remains a hypothesis.\\n- **Plugin semantic-blindness is a known, accepted limit** — the smoke/benchmark, not the plugin, is what actually validates leaf-dispatch correctness.\\n- **Mis-route taxonomy (modes A/B/C) and the FIX-1…FIX-5 ranking remain operator-asserted axioms**, carried from the predecessor research (`../001-deep-agent-router-and-orchestration/research/research.md` §0) and not re-validated by this research pass. The KQ1 smoke is the stated path to validating them, not this document.\\n- **Codex parity** stays deferred (pre-existing TOML-location contradiction, out of scope for this packet).\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 5. Convergence Report (both lineages)\\n\\n| Lineage | Model | Iterations | Stop reason | Questions answered | Notes |\\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\\n| glm-max | `zai-coding-plan/glm-5.2`, reasoning `max` | 30/30 | `maxIterationsReached` | 9/9 | 0 salvaged/failed iterations; adversarial re-checks at iters 8, 11, 13, 19, 22, 25, 26 |\\n| gpt-fast-high | `openai/gpt-5.5-fast`, reasoning `high` | 30/30 | `max_iterations` | 9/9 | 30/30 iterations required stdout-salvage recovery for the canonical JSONL append (a runtime robustness note, not a research-quality issue — narrative content and citations are intact) |\\n\\nBoth lineages' `newInfoRatio` trends declined well below typical early-stop thresholds by iteration ~10-12 (glm-max) and ~15 (gpt-fast-high) — under this packet's *previous* default configuration (`antiConvergence.minIterations: 3`, `stopPolicy: convergence`), both runs would very likely have stopped early, in the 5-15 iteration range, missing the adversarial re-checks and analytical-consolidation passes (iterations ~19-30) that produced several of the higher-confidence, cross-checked findings above (KQ3's risk-asymmetry argument, KQ4's authority-preservation argument, KQ9's negative-gate framing). This is itself a confirming data point for the packet's own `--stop-policy=max-iterations` fix (this research's own launch required correcting a live instance of exactly this early-convergence behavior — see phase 007's `implementation-summary.md`).\\n\\n---\\n\\n<!-- ANCHOR:references -->\\n## References\\n\\n- Predecessor research: `../001-deep-agent-router-and-orchestration/research/research.md`\\n- Research charter: `research-prompt.md`\\n- Goal / operator symptom report: `../goal-prompt.md`\\n- Phase 005 (inconclusive smoke): `../005-gpt-verification-smoke/implementation-summary.md`, `verification-smoke.md`\\n- Phase 006 (FIX-5 decision record): `../006-host-hard-identity-fix5/decision-record.md`\\n- Full lineage syntheses: `lineages/glm-max/research.md`, `lineages/gpt-fast-high/research.md`\\n- Merged findings registry: `deep-research-findings-registry.json`\\n- Fan-out attribution: `fanout-attribution.md`\\n<!-- /ANCHOR:references -->\",\"lineStart\":1,\"lineEnd\":110,\"totalLines\":110,\"truncated\":false}},\"title\":\".opencode/specs/deep-loops/031-deep-loop-issues-with-gpt-opencode/007-gpt-behavioral-hardening-research/research/research.md\",\"time\":{\"start\":1782897205735,\"end\":1782897205743}},\"metadata\":{\"openai\":{\"itemId\":\"fc_09aaf1ad62ff6cb6016a44da34e0d48191b3f7064fbb0639d1\"}},\"id\":\"prt_f1cf460f1001uEtCtkXdgvFp7s\",\"sessionID\":\"ses_0e30e0717ffe0AOyqAZM72PE2n\",\"messageID\":\"msg_f1cf3c1f9001ci5srK4XXosdx7\"}}\n.opencode/specs/deep-loops/031-deep-loop-issues-with-gpt-opencode/007-gpt-behavioral-hardening-research/research/lineages/gpt-critical/logs/fanout-lineage.out:36:{\"type\":\"tool_use\",\"timestamp\":1782897205779,\"sessionID\":\"ses_0e30e0717ffe0AOyqAZM72PE2n\",\"part\":{\"type\":\"tool\",\"tool\":\"read\",\"callID\":\"call_OXeyEkyuri3CNyi2lfsI34HH\",\"state\":{\"status\":\"completed\",\"input\":{\"filePath\":\"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/deep-loops/031-deep-loop-issues-with-gpt-opencode/007-gpt-behavioral-hardening-research/research/lineages/glm-max/research.md\",\"offset\":1,\"limit\":2000},\"output\":\"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/deep-loops/031-deep-loop-issues-with-gpt-opencode/007-gpt-behavioral-hardening-research/research/lineages/glm-max/research.md</path>\\n<type>file</type>\\n<content>\\n1: # Research: GPT Behavioral Hardening Follow-Up (Packet 031) — glm-max lineage\\n2: \\n3: > **Synthesis of a 30-iteration deep-research fan-out lineage** (cli-opencode / zai-coding-plan/glm-5.2 / reasoning max). Stop policy: `max-iterations` (30); convergence signals treated as telemetry only; angles broadened via adversarial re-checks (iters 8,11,13,19,22,25,26) and analytical consolidation (iters 27-29). Spec folder: `.../007-gpt-behavioral-hardening-research`. Sibling lineage: `gpt-fast-high`. Iteration evidence: `iterations/iteration-001.md` … `iteration-030.md`. All 9 KQs answered with `file:line` citations.\\n4: \\n5: ---\\n6: \\n7: ## 0. CRITICAL INTEGRITY CAVEAT — READ FIRST\\n8: \\n9: This lineage builds on the predecessor research (`../001-deep-agent-router-and-orchestration/research/research.md`) whose §0 records that the mis-route taxonomy (modes A/B/C) and FIX-1…FIX-5 ranking are **operator-asserted axioms*","exit":0,"truncated":true,"outputPath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/.local/share/opencode/tool-output/tool_f1ef54247002rkP84AnPJsMaKJ"},"title":"grep -rn \"goal-prompt.md\" \".opencode/specs/deep-loops/031-deep-loop-issues-with-gpt-opencode\" 2>/dev/null","time":{"start":1782930817507,"end":1782930817608}},"id":"prt_f1ef541e1001pGsf0jwpoE8Z9l","sessionID":"ses_0e10e5929ffe88XcmihhZxWbsA","messageID":"msg_f1ef5267b001Mh26bcGSduU5Fj"}}
